12:02.021 --> 12:12.966 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
HARI SREENIVASAN: Education
Secretary John
King has only been officially in
his position

12:13.066 --> 12:17.470 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
about a month-and-a-half, taking
over for
Arne Duncan, who served for the
first seven

12:17.570 --> 12:20.106 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
years of President Obama's
administration.

12:20.206 --> 12:25.478 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
But King has inherited a very
full plate,
including the successor to No
Child Left Behind,

12:25.578 --> 12:30.717 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
increasing resegregation of
public schools,
and a higher education
admissions process

12:30.817 --> 12:32.819 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
he likens to a caste system.

12:32.919 --> 12:38.658 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
I sat down with him earlier
today as part
of our Making the Grade series
on education.

12:38.758 --> 12:42.562 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
While the majority of the states
are implementing
Common Core, it hasn't been
without resistance.

12:42.662 --> 12:47.500 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
There are still hundreds of
thousands of parents
out there who are having their
children opt

12:47.600 --> 12:49.669 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
out of some of these tests.

12:49.769 --> 12:55.141 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And my question is, doesn't that
structurally
defeat the system if, at a
certain threshold,

12:55.241 --> 12:57.710 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
you can't get good data anymore
because people
are opting out?

12:57.810 --> 13:00.213 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
JOHN KING, U.S. Education
Secretary: So, the
effort to raise standards is
really about

13:00.313 --> 13:03.816 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
ensuring that all students
graduate ready
for what's next.

13:03.916 --> 13:08.154 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
As you said, we have 40-plus
states that are
working on higher standards.
There are challenges,

13:08.254 --> 13:13.292 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
for sure, in raising standards,
changes that
need to be made to instruction,
to classroom

13:13.393 --> 13:17.997 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
materials, and to assessments.
And states
are making smart adjustments
along the way.

13:18.097 --> 13:22.101 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
I think we generally have
positive momentum.
We have the highest graduation
rate we have

13:22.201 --> 13:26.272 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
ever had as a country last year.
But it's
not surprising that there are
going to be

13:26.372 --> 13:31.644 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
challenges along the way, and
states are going
to need to be responsive to what
they're hearing

13:31.744 --> 13:36.015 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
from parents and educators, make
adjustments,
while staying focused on raising
standards.

13:36.115 --> 13:40.553 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
HARI SREENIVASAN: No Child Left
Behind, we
all now in hindsight know that
we didn't reach

13:40.653 --> 13:45.825 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
100 percent proficiency by 2014.
But one of
the things that that did do for
us is give

13:45.925 --> 13:51.531 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
us a little bit of visibility
into how specific
schools and specific subgroups
were performing.

13:51.631 --> 13:58.304 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
So, now, with the Every Student
Succeeds Act,
it seems that you're letting
possibly thousands

13:58.404 --> 14:02.842 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
of schools who were
underperforming off the
hook by focusing on just the 5
percent that

14:02.942 --> 14:05.078 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
are really going to get -- be
targeted the
aid.

14:05.178 --> 14:09.849 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JOHN KING: The structure of the
Every Student
Succeeds Act is to give states
and local districts

14:09.949 --> 14:13.219 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
more flexibility, but within
clear civil rights
guardrails.

14:13.319 --> 14:18.024 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
There is a very clear
requirement for states
and districts to intervene when
schools are

14:18.124 --> 14:23.496 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
struggling, as you say, in the
bottom 5 percent,
but also schools that have
chronically low

14:23.596 --> 14:29.068 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
graduation rates, schools that
have significant
achievement gaps, where
subgroups, African-American

14:29.168 --> 14:34.307 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
students, Latino students,
English learners,
if those subgroups are
underperforming, states

14:34.407 --> 14:37.777 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
and districts also have an
obligation to intervene.

14:37.877 --> 14:42.381 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
The president signed the law
because he believes
it builds on the civil rights
legacy of the

14:42.482 --> 14:47.787 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
law, which was first adopted in
1965 as a
civil rights law. And so those
civil rights

14:47.887 --> 14:51.124 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
guardrails are key, we think, to
successful
implementation.

14:51.224 --> 14:55.528 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
HARI SREENIVASAN: It actually
takes a significant
amount of power out of this very
office and

14:55.628 --> 15:02.568 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
gives it back to the states in
several ways.
So, you can't actually impose
any specific

15:02.668 --> 15:07.406 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
guidelines about Common Core or
about things
that states have to do.

15:07.507 --> 15:12.245 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
So, I'm trying to figure out,
what's the right
balance between the federal
government's involvement

15:12.345 --> 15:15.815 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
and state governments'
administration of education?

15:15.915 --> 15:19.318 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JOHN KING: Well, we think, on
standards, that
that's a good example of where
we have tried

15:19.418 --> 15:21.287 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
to strike the right balance.

15:21.387 --> 15:24.824 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
So, the law requires that states
adopt standards
that will ensure that, when
students graduate

15:24.924 --> 15:28.461 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
from high school, they're ready
for college
and careers, they're ready to do
credit-bearing

15:28.561 --> 15:33.466 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
course work in college. That's
good, because
it means every state has to have
high standards.

15:33.566 --> 15:38.638 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
That said, the specific details
of those standards
are left to states. We think
that's right.

15:38.738 --> 15:43.276 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
That's what we have always
thought, that states
should be the ones determining
their standards.

15:43.376 --> 15:48.481 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
On accountability, it's clear
states and districts
have a responsibility to
intervene where schools

15:48.581 --> 15:52.819 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
are struggling or where there
are achievement
gaps, but the exact nature of
those interventions,

15:52.919 --> 15:55.288 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
they can design based on local
circumstances.

15:55.388 --> 15:59.358 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
HARI SREENIVASAN: One of the
things that people
are concerned about structurally
is that there

15:59.458 --> 16:05.665 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
almost seems to be a
resegregation of education
in America right now, that, in
the last three

16:05.765 --> 16:09.735 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
years, two things have changed
primarily,
that minorities now outnumber
whites in the

16:09.836 --> 16:14.040 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
nation's public schools, and the
majority
of public school students are
poor, and that

16:14.140 --> 16:15.975 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
they qualify for free lunches.

16:16.075 --> 16:19.879 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
How do we change this narrative
about almost
two separate education systems?

16:19.979 --> 16:22.648 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
JOHN KING: It's a huge problem.

16:22.748 --> 16:29.488 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
We know that we have tons of
research evidence
over decades showing that
students do better

16:29.589 --> 16:36.529 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
in diverse schools, and yet 60
years after
Brown vs. Board of Education, we
still have

16:36.629 --> 16:39.866 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
racially isolated, economically
isolated schools.

16:39.966 --> 16:43.569 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
What's encouraging -- the
Century Foundation
just did a report on this
recently. What's

16:43.669 --> 16:48.507 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
encouraging is, you have efforts
all over
the country, locally-led
voluntary efforts,

16:48.608 --> 16:51.978 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
to create socioeconomically
integrated schools.

16:52.078 --> 16:56.382 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And we want to -- we want to
accelerate that
work, so we have made school
diversity a priority

16:56.482 --> 17:00.820 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
for investing in an innovation
grant program.
The president's proposed an
initiative called

17:00.920 --> 17:06.759 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Stronger Together, $120 million
in his 2017
budget that would support local
efforts to

17:06.859 --> 17:09.562 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
create socioeconomically diverse
schools.

17:09.662 --> 17:13.733 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Schools -- you can imagine an
art school that
might draw students from across
different

17:13.833 --> 17:19.138 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
communities, a dual-language
school where
native English speakers and
English learners

17:19.238 --> 17:21.540 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
would together have the
opportunity to learn
two languages.

17:21.641 --> 17:24.610 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
HARI SREENIVASAN: Even in terms
of higher
ed, you have said before that
there's almost

17:24.710 --> 17:29.148 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
a caste system of colleges and
universities
in the admissions process. So,
how do we change

17:29.248 --> 17:31.183 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
that?

17:31.284 --> 17:33.119 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JOHN KING: I think of a place
like Franklin
&amp; Marshall that's committed to
enrolling low-income

17:33.219 --> 17:37.490 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
students, has raised their
academic standards
at the same time as they have
enrolled more

17:37.590 --> 17:41.260 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
low-income students, and they're
providing
the supports necessary to ensure
that those

17:41.360 --> 17:43.162 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
students graduate.

17:43.262 --> 17:47.266 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And so I think there's a bully
pulpit role
for the administration to play.
But we have

17:47.366 --> 17:50.636 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
also got to make sure the
resources are there.
And that's why the Pell Grant
program is so

17:50.736 --> 17:55.074 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
important. It's why the
president has added
$1,000 to the average Pell Grant
since the

17:55.174 --> 17:56.976 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
administration began.

17:57.076 --> 18:01.080 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
It's why we think it's important
to let students
access Pell Grants in the
summer, because

18:01.180 --> 18:06.585 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
that will help low-income
students stay on
track to graduation. So, there's
both a -- there's

18:06.686 --> 18:10.389 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
both a moral responsibility that
higher ed
institutions have, and a
responsibility that

18:10.489 --> 18:16.228 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
government has to provide the
resources to
support all of our citizens in
making it through

18:16.329 --> 18:17.997 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
higher education.

18:18.097 --> 18:20.633 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
HARI SREENIVASAN: Finally,
unlike a lot of
education secretaries or Cabinet
members,

18:20.733 --> 18:24.971 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
you have got a kind of a
personal connection
to education. You lost your
parents when you

18:25.071 --> 18:29.408 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
were a very young age, and you
have said before
that it's really teachers that
saved your

18:29.508 --> 18:29.909 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
life.

18:30.009 --> 18:31.777 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
Explain that.

18:31.877 --> 18:34.347 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JOHN KING: School really did
save my life.
My mom passed away when I was 8
in October

18:34.447 --> 18:40.753 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
of my fourth-grade year. I lived
with my dad,
who was suffering with
undiagnosed Alzheimer's

18:40.853 --> 18:42.722 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
disease.

18:42.822 --> 18:47.426 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And so home was this very scary
and unpredictable
place. My dad passed away when I
was 12. And

18:47.526 --> 18:50.429 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
during that period, my life
could have gone
in a lot of directions. You
know, teachers

18:50.529 --> 18:54.400 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
could have looked at me and
said, here's an
African-American Latino male
student, family

18:54.500 --> 18:59.238 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
in crisis, going to a New York
City public
school in Brooklyn. What chance
does he have?

18:59.338 --> 19:04.677 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
But they didn't. They chose to
invest in me
and made school this place that
was engaging

19:04.777 --> 19:09.615 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
and compelling and interesting,
where we read
The New York Times every day, we
did productions

19:09.715 --> 19:14.887 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
of "Midsummer Night's Dream" and
"Alice in
Wonderland." We went to the
ballet and the

19:14.987 --> 19:16.822 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
museum.

19:16.922 --> 19:20.659 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
School was engaging and a place
where I could
be a kid when I couldn't be a
kid outside

19:20.760 --> 19:22.628 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
of school.

19:22.728 --> 19:27.233 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
So, I'm very clear: I'm alive
today, doing
this work today, became a
teacher and a principal

19:27.333 --> 19:33.472 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
because the teachers I had saved
my life.
And, you know, I bring to work
every day the

19:33.572 --> 19:37.009 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
goal of trying to do for other
kids what my
teachers did for me.

19:37.109 --> 19:42.448 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
HARI SREENIVASAN: Secretary
King, thanks for
joining us.

19:42.548 --> 19:48.421 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
JOHN KING: Thanks so much.

19:48.521 --> 19:51.690 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
