of the separate
species of human being. And one
of the things

42:34.452 --> 42:41.426 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
about baby boomers is that we
want to be young.
Let's face it. And we're young
grandparents,

42:41.526 --> 42:46.364 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
because we're baby boomers. And,
of course,
we determine everything as we go
through our

42:46.464 --> 42:48.733 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
history. We're such a big bulge.

42:48.833 --> 42:55.306 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
We're young. We're energetic.
We're spending
infinitely more money on our
grandchildren

42:55.406 --> 43:01.345 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
than grandparents of old. I saw
a statistic
the other day. It's not even in
the book.

43:01.446 --> 43:05.750 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Grandparents today spend seven
times more
on their grandchildren than they
did just

43:05.850 --> 43:07.618 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
10 years ago. So...

43:07.718 --> 43:13.991 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: Part of your
title is "The
Joys and Science of the New
Grandparenting."

43:14.091 --> 43:15.326 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
LESLEY STAHL: Oh, yes.

43:15.426 --> 43:16.627 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: Is that wishful
thinking, or
is that real?

43:16.727 --> 43:18.729 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
LESLEY STAHL: No, no.

43:18.830 --> 43:25.770 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
What was that feeling I had?
Well, I was stunned
to discover and delighted that
there are biological

43:25.870 --> 43:32.510 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
changes that go along when
you're a mother,
but grandmothers have something
similar. And

43:32.610 --> 43:38.049 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
it's real. What you're feeling
is a change
in your body. You're being
rewired to connect

43:38.149 --> 43:39.417 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
to this baby.

43:39.517 --> 43:41.352 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: It's not just
because they're
cute and cuddly?

43:41.452 --> 43:45.223 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
LESLEY STAHL: Well, it's also
because they're
cute and cuddly, but they're
yours. There's

43:45.323 --> 43:47.358 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
a real binding that goes on
there.

43:47.458 --> 43:51.829 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: You were just
telling me that
the cover picture, it looks like
you're sitting

43:51.929 --> 43:54.198 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
there and you're reading to your
granddaughters.

43:54.298 --> 43:55.566 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
LESLEY STAHL: Uh-huh. Looks that
way, right?

43:55.666 --> 43:57.435 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
(LAUGHTER)

43:57.535 --> 44:00.738 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
LESLEY STAHL: So, they wouldn't
cooperate.
They wouldn't both sit quietly
together at

44:00.838 --> 44:04.909 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
the same time. So, we put an
iPhone -- we
taped it to the middle of the
book, and they're

44:05.009 --> 44:05.710 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
watching "Frozen."

44:05.810 --> 44:07.545 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
(LAUGHTER)

44:07.645 --> 44:09.714 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
LESLEY STAHL: It's the only --
and I think
that's the only picture we got
where they

44:09.814 --> 44:11.682 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
were both cooperating.

44:11.782 --> 44:15.786 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: You do focus so
much in the
book, Lesley, on the positives
of grandparenting.

44:15.887 --> 44:17.722 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
And you have had a very positive
experience.

44:17.822 --> 44:19.757 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
LESLEY STAHL: I have.

44:19.857 --> 44:21.859 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: But we all know
there are grandparents
out there who, for whatever
reason, aren't

44:21.959 --> 44:27.331 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
being allowed to see their
grandchildren or
who are forced to completely
raise their grandchildren

44:27.431 --> 44:29.433 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
under difficult circumstances.

44:29.534 --> 44:30.902 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
It's a mixed picture, isn't it?

44:31.002 --> 44:34.005 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
LESLEY STAHL: Well, I write
about that and
discovered it, actually.

44:34.105 --> 44:39.377 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
I have been asked, what's the
thing that most
surprised me? And that
grandparents are denied

44:39.477 --> 44:45.082 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
access to their own
grandchildren, which is
fairly prevalent, really
surprised me and

44:45.182 --> 44:52.156 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
shocked me. just it's -- I get
-- I actually
get pained even telling you
about this, because

44:52.256 --> 44:57.995 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
the grandmothers who admitted it
to me -- and
a lot of them are ashamed about
this -- told

44:58.095 --> 45:00.398 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
me with tears streaming down
their faces.

45:00.498 --> 45:02.233 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
It's a horrible thing.

45:02.333 --> 45:05.803 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
JUDY WOODRUFF: This book,
Lesley, is -- it's
a very personal story. I mean,
it is very

45:05.903 --> 45:11.442 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
much about your own family, your
grandchildren,
your relationship with your
mother, what kind

45:11.542 --> 45:13.444 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
of a grandmother she was.

45:13.544 --> 45:18.416 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
You also write about your
husband, Aaron Latham,
and you openly say is dealing
with Parkinson's.

45:18.516 --> 45:21.719 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
So, there's a lot you lay bare
here, isn't
there?

45:21.819 --> 45:25.356 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
LESLEY STAHL: Well, one of the
things that
-- one of the reasons I wrote
about my own

45:25.456 --> 45:31.228 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
relationship with my mother,
which was a little
difficult, unlike mine with my
daughter, which

45:31.329 --> 45:35.232 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
is wonderful -- but my mother
and I clashed
a lot.

45:35.333 --> 45:41.939 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
But she was a completely
besotted grandmother.
I would look at her and say, who
is that?

45:42.039 --> 45:48.012 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And I heard that over and over
from women
my age. "My mother is so
different with my

45:48.112 --> 45:54.051 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
children." And that's part of
being a grandmother.
You go from being who you are to
being a mush

45:54.151 --> 45:56.153 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
ball, like that.

45:56.253 --> 46:01.892 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And people say, who is he? We
don't know ourselves.
We get so mushy. And this is
part of the reason

46:01.993 --> 46:05.563 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
I wanted to write it. We -- they
just soften
us completely.

46:05.663 --> 46:10.401 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: You can be -- I
guess part
of the message is you can be a
different kind

46:10.501 --> 46:13.170 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
of grandmother from the kind of
mother you
were?

46:13.270 --> 46:16.407 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
LESLEY STAHL: Totally different.
And it's
out of your control, even if you
didn't want

46:16.507 --> 46:16.941 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
to be.

46:17.041 --> 46:18.843 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
(LAUGHTER)

46:18.943 --> 46:22.480 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: I was struck at
the end, you
urge grandparents to jump in if
they're not

46:22.580 --> 46:28.953 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
already involved in the lives of
their grandchildren,
and urge parents, likewise, to
let their own

46:29.053 --> 46:30.788 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
parents be involved.

46:30.888 --> 46:37.028 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
LESLEY STAHL: Well, children
today, young
parents need our help, because
they're not

46:37.128 --> 46:40.431 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
making much money. They're both
working. They're
suffering economically.

46:40.531 --> 46:47.238 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
So, they need our help. Those
babies need
their grandparents. We are very
important

46:47.338 --> 46:53.244 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
to their development. And we
need them, because
they make us healthier. And so
it's a win-win-win.

46:53.344 --> 46:54.979 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
Why not?

46:55.079 --> 46:58.582 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: Well, there are
some great
stories here, Lesley Stahl, "The
Joys and

46:58.683 --> 47:01.786 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
the Science of the New
Grandparenting."

47:01.886 --> 47:03.954 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
Thank you very much.

47:04.055 --> 47:12.063 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
LESLEY STAHL: Thank you, Judy.

47:12.163 --> 47:20.805 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
HARI SREENIVASAN: Finally, the
latest in our
occasional series on poets and
what inspires

47:20.905 --> 47:22.673 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
them.

47:22.773 --> 47:26.811 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Tonight, Ocean Vuong, recently
chosen for
the prestigious Whiting Award.
His new book,

47:26.911 --> 47:32.283 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
"Night Sky With Exit Wounds,"
explores the
legacy of the Vietnam War and
the power of

47:32.383 --> 47:34.085 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
oral history.

47:34.185 --> 47:35.953 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
OCEAN VUONG, Author, "Night Sky
With Exit
Wounds": Sometimes, people say,
well, how

47:36.053 --> 47:39.423 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
does it feel to be the first
poet? And I say,
I'm not the first poet. I come
from a long

47:39.523 --> 47:41.726 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
line of poets. They were not
documented.

47:41.826 --> 47:49.133 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And it's interesting how poems
are carried
from one culture to another. In
Vietnam, there's

47:49.233 --> 47:56.741 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
much dependency on the body. One
needs to
have the body -- in a way, the
body is a book,

47:56.841 --> 48:02.046 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
that one needs the body to
remember the poem,
sing the poems and pass them
along.

48:02.146 --> 48:07.585 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
My grandmother, she was a rice
farmer. In
a sense, all Vietnamese farmers
were poets,

48:07.685 --> 48:12.390 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
because while they were working,
they sang,
and the songs helped the rhythm
of the harvesting

48:12.490 --> 48:14.492 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
and the seeding of the fields.

48:14.592 --> 48:20.598 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
But, also, the daily news of
life, and ultimately,
when the war came, where the
bombs were falling,

48:20.698 --> 48:25.002 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
information started to come into
the rhyming
couplets in the poems and the
songs. And this

48:25.102 --> 48:26.804 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
is how information was passed.

48:26.904 --> 48:32.209 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
In the poem "Aubade with Burning
City," I
took Irving Berlin's "White
Christmas," the

48:32.309 --> 48:37.214 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
lyrics, and wove it through a
scene about
the collapse of Saigon.

48:37.314 --> 48:42.219 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
When my grandmother would tell
me about the
collapse of Saigon, she would
say, "Saigon,

48:42.319 --> 48:48.125 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
this sounds very strange, but I
remember it
fell during the snow song." And
as a child

48:48.225 --> 48:52.663 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
listening to that, it was so
surreal to me.
That was the song that was used
as a coded

48:52.763 --> 48:55.466 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
message for American personnel
to evacuate.

48:55.566 --> 49:01.438 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
So, you can imagine the city
falling apart
during this beautiful,
celebratory song.

49:01.539 --> 49:09.213 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
"I'm dreaming of a white
Christmas. Outside,
a soldier spits out his
cigarette as footsteps

49:09.313 --> 49:16.987 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
fill the square like stones
fallen from the
sky. May all your Christmases be
white as

49:17.087 --> 49:24.695 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
the traffic guard unstraps his
holster, his
fingers running the hem of her
white dress.

49:24.795 --> 49:32.970 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
A single candle. Their shadows,
two wicks.
A military truck speeds through
the intersection,

49:33.070 --> 49:35.439 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
children shrieking inside.

49:35.539 --> 49:44.348 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
"A bicycle hurled through a
store window.
When the dust rises, a black dog
lies panting

49:44.448 --> 49:51.488 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
in the road, its hind legs
crushed into the
shine of a white Christmas."

49:51.589 --> 49:56.227 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
When my grandmother passed away
in 2008, and
I wanted to preserve that memory
landscape

49:56.327 --> 50:01.999 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
on paper, I was faced with where
to break
her lines. And, of course, the
oral tradition

50:02.099 --> 50:10.474 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
doesn't offer a page. In a way,
I was collaborating
with this -- with my grandmother
beyond her

50:10.574 --> 50:12.309 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
life.

50:12.409 --> 50:16.881 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
When we immigrated to America,
all she had
were these songs and poems. My
mother was

50:16.981 --> 50:24.221 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
also illiterate. She -- her
father is an American
veteran. When we arrived in
America, she went

50:24.321 --> 50:31.929 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
right into the nail salon to
work, manual
labor. And she made it her goal
to teach me

50:32.029 --> 50:33.864 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
how to write.

50:33.964 --> 50:39.470 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And the poem "The Gift" is very
interesting
because she only knew A, B, C,
three letters.

50:39.570 --> 50:41.572 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
But she would have me write
those letters
anyway.

50:41.672 --> 50:55.019 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
"A, B, C, A, B, C, A -- the
pencil snaps,
the B bursting its belly as dark
dust blows

50:55.119 --> 51:03.560 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
through a blue-lined sky. Don't
move, she
says, as she picks a wing bone
of graphite

51:03.661 --> 51:09.033 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
from the yellow carcass, slides
it back between
my fingers."

51:09.133 --> 51:17.007 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
We look at this wall, the
interesting and
tense relationship I have with
the war is

51:17.107 --> 51:21.812 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
that, without it, I wouldn't be
here. And
if I were to turn around and
walk down this

51:21.912 --> 51:29.320 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
memorial and find my
grandfather's name, I
wouldn't be alive if his name
was there.

51:29.420 --> 51:34.591 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
That is -- the facts and the
truths of what
it means to be an American, is
to be involved

51:34.692 --> 51:46.737 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
in this, and that perhaps --
it's seemingly
so strange that a war in Vietnam
and an American

51:46.837 --> 51:54.678 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
soldier would bring cause to a
poet like me,
a Vietnamese-American poet.

51:54.778 --> 52:02.186 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
"When they ask you where you're
from, tell
them your name was fleshed from
the toothless

52:02.286 --> 52:13.897 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
mouth of a war woman, that you
were not born,
but crawled headfirst into the
hunger of dogs.

52:13.998 --> 52:21.171 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
My son, tell them the body is a
blade that
sharpens by cutting."

52:21.271 --> 52:25.943 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
All of these people coming
together out of
violence, trying to do their
best to make

52:26.043 --> 52:28.445 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
meaning out of their existence.

